Measuring Apical Constriction

David Kleinhans

2017-11-13

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo=FALSE, cache=TRUE, autodep=TRUE, cache.comments=FALSE, warning=FALSE, out.width='75%\\textwidth', fig.align='center', eval=FALSE, include=TRUE)

1 Rationale

1.1 Apical Constriction

During development cells differentiate and undergo drastic shape changes from one morphological typus to another, a process commonly known as morphogenesis. Collective cellular morphologies give rise to tissue morphology, which gives rise to organ morphology and so on. One distinct morphogenetic feature is apical constriction (AC), an active narrowing of cellular apices. Apical constriction occurs in all multicellular organisms and most often during early embryogenesis1 e.g. during…

  • C.elegans gastrulation2
  • D.Melanogaster & Vertebrate neural tube formation
  • Epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition and ingression

A principal definition is given by J.y. Lee and R.M.Harland2 and illustrated in figure 1.

Apical constriction is the process in which contraction of the apical side of a cell causes the cell to take on a wedged shape. Generally, this shape change is coordinated across many cells of an epithelial layer, generating forces that can bend or fold the cell sheet.

Figure 1: Apical constriction and tissue bending. A D. Melanogaster mesoderm invagination. B Vertebrate neurulation. C and D schematic representation of AC in an epithelial tissue3.

1.2 Measuring AC

1.2.1 Apical Constriction Index

The earliest attempt found for indexing AC can be found in a study published by Lee et al.4 where they were were looking for the ‘apical index’(A.I.) of bottle cells during xenopus gastrulation.

Figure 2: Apical Index of Xenopus bottle cells

An application for the apical constriction index (ACI) for the cells in the lateral line primordium was in a study from 2012 where it was shown that Fgfr-Ras-MAPK signaling is required for AC and Rock2a localization5,6.

Figure 3: Apical constriction index. (A) 3D reconstructed cells of a DMSO control primordium and (B) 3D reconstructed cells of a primordium deficient of Fgf signaling.

The calculation for the ACI used in 6 does not differ from the A.I. used in 4 and describes the ratio for lateral height over apical width.

\[ACI = \frac{lateral\;height\;[µm]}{apical\;width\;[µm]}\]

While trying to reproduce these results we figured two principal weaknesses of applying this measurement to the cells of the lateral line primordium. One, it does not respect that apical constriction is independent of lateral height. Second, it does not differenciate between dorso-ventral and cranial-caudal tissue polarization.

1.2.2 Parameter definition

To obtain a precise and biologically meaningful quantity for AC, a couple of parameter definitions have to be made…

  1. AC is independent of orientation and polarization
    • Cells can be dorso-ventral (DV) polarized
    • Cells can also be cranial-caudal (CC) polarized
  2. AC is independent of lateral height
    • Lateral height can be described as the distance of the two farthest points of the surface area of a cell
    • Two cells with different lateral heights can be equally apically constricted
  3. AC is independent of cell volume / size
    • The size of a cell is its volume
    • Two cells of different volume can be equally apically constricted

1.2.3 Adaption for variation in lateral height

An apically constricted cell can be approximated by modeling a tetrahedron to test different ACI conditions. For example, shrinking or enlarging a cell symmetrically should not affect the ACI. As described by Harding[2014]6, the \(\mathit{apical\;width}\) of a cell is measured first by manual 3-D object reconstruction, manual re-orientation, by going 1 µm from the apical tip into the cell (from now on refered to as \(\mathrm{\Delta}\)ap) and and finally by measuring the the width of the 2-D Roi.

Figure 3: Illustrating delta ap. left panel: An apically constricted cells volume rendered in XY (top) and as a lateral cross-section in X-Z (bottom). right panel: the 2-D area as seen when going for 1 or 2.5 µm delta ap into the cell

If \(\mathrm{\Delta}\)ap is a constant, the ACI in a symmetrically enlarged cell increases from e.g. 15 to 23 (Fig.4b ) since \(\mathit{apical\;width}\) stays the same but lateral height increases. On the contrary, if \(\mathrm{\Delta}\)ap changes relative to a cells lateral height, e.g. by percentage (10% - 20%), the ACI in a symmetrically enlarged cell stays the same (Fig.4C).

Figure 4: ACI Cell Models. B and C show cells that are symmetrically increased versions of A. While in B, constant delta was used, in C delta was adjusted relative to the lateral height.

Therefore the measurement for apical width has to be relative to lateral height.

\[ACI = \frac{lateral\;height\;[µm]}{relative\;apical\;width\;[µm]}\]

1.2.4 Adaption for tissue polarization

Organs develop in a 3-D space and are polarized along each axis. AC usually describes a 2-D morphogenetic movement along the X-Y axes towards a center. However, the contraction movements along X and Y might be independent of one another. This could mean that they happen at different speeds or that one is absent. As a result the tissue would look less radially (2-D) constricted, but more constricted against a line (1-D).

In order to seperate the ACI into a horizontal \(\mathrm{ACI_H}\) and a vertical \(\mathrm{ACI_V}\) measurement, one could not only measure \(\mathit{apical\;width}\), but also \(\mathit{apical\;height}\). By fitting an ellipsoid to the region of interest taken at \(\mathrm{\Delta}\)ap, one will obtain the following parameters…

  1. length of Major axis
    • constituting vertical constriction
  2. length of Minor axis
    • constituting horizontal constriction
  3. Angle of Major from 0° (horizont)
    • indicating the direction of contraction

Figure 4: Schematic vertical and horizontal AC. Panel (A) shows a vertically and horizontally constricted cluster of cells. Panel (B) shows a horizontally constricted cluster of cells.

To calculate the two dimensions of apical constriction indices one would therefore have to calculate…

  1. vertical ACI \[ACI_V = \frac{lateral\;height\;[µm]}{Major\;axis\;[µm]}\]
  2. and horizontal ACI \[ACI_H = \frac{lateral\;height\;[µm]}{Minor\;axis\;[µm]}\]

Define function to import and process data

library(plyr)
library(dplyr)
read.data.all.3D <- function(file){
    dat <- read.table(file, sep="\t", header=TRUE)
    dat$Nb <- NULL
    dat$Obj <- file
    dat$X <- NULL
    Zcal <- dat$CZ..unit./dat$CZ..pix.                # To transform pix to unit value in Z
    XYcal <- dat$CX..unit./dat$CX..pix.               # To transform pix to unit value in X and Y
    dat$Height <- (dat$Zmax..pix.-dat$Zmin..pix.)*Zcal  # calculate Height and transform to unit value
    dat$Height <- dat$Height*Zcal                       # calculate Height and transform to unit value
    dat$Length <- (dat$Xmax..pix.-dat$Xmin..pix.)*XYcal # calculate Length and transform to unit value
    dat$Width <- (dat$Ymax..pix.-dat$Ymin..pix.)*XYcal  # calculate Width and transform to unit value
    dat$HF <- dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.               # calculate Height/Feret ratio
    # calculate Phi
    dat$Phi <- ((atan(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.))*180)/pi
    adj <- dat$Length/2
    opp <- dat$Height
    hyp <- dat$Feret..unit.
    dat$Phi <- ((atan(adj/opp))*180)/pi
    #dat$Phi <- ((asin(1/hyp))*180)/pi
    #dat$ACPhi <- 180-((((atan(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.))*180)/pi)+90) # <- ACPhi3
    dat$ACPhi <- 180-((((atan(adj/opp))*180)/pi)+90)  #                     <- ACPhi2
    #dat$ACPhi <- asin(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.)    #                    <- ACPhi1
    trail <- ((max(dat$CX..pix.)-min(dat$CX..pix.))*XYcal[1])*0.25
    dat$CXN <- (max(dat$CX..pix.)-dat$CX..pix.)*XYcal   # normalize CX against leading edge
    #dat <- subset(dat, dat$CXN < quantile(dat$CXN, 0.99, na.rm=TRUE) & dat$CXN > quantile(dat$CXN, 0.01, na.rm=TRUE))
    #lower <- subset(dat, dat$CXN > quantile(dat$CXN, 0.99, na.rm=TRUE))
    #print(lower$Label)
    #upper <- subset(dat, dat$CXN < quantile(dat$CXN, 0.01, na.rm=TRUE))
    #print(upper$Label)
    #trail <- quantile(dat$CXN, 0.2, na.rm=TRUE)
    print(trail)
    dat$FLsplit <- cut(dat$CXN, breaks = c(-Inf, trail, Inf), labels = c("leading", "trailing"))
    dat$SAV <- dat$Surf..unit./dat$Vol..unit.           # calculate Surface Area to Volume ratio 
    dat$VolN <- (1/min(dat$Vol..unit., na.rm=TRUE))*dat$Vol..unit.  # normalize Volumes
    dat$GT <- GT                                        # add Genotype
    dat$CZ..pix. <- NULL
    dat$CX..pix. <- NULL
    dat$CY..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Xmin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Xmax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Ymin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Ymax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Zmin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Zmax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Vol..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Surf..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Spher..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Comp..pix. <- NULL
    return(dat)
  }
read.data.all.ACI <- function(file){
    dat <- read.table(file, header=TRUE)
    dat$objlabelArray <- NULL
    dat$ACI <- dat$basalArray/dat$apicalArray
    return(dat)
  }

4 Data Analysis

4.1 Point clouds in XY

4.1.1 Adapted Apical constriction index

Each geometric object has a centroid coordinate in X and Y (and Z) which is represented as the mean of all X or all Y coordinates within the object. Here the centroid coordinates in X and Y are used to plot the cells as points in the X-Y plane. Additionally each point is colored for the ACI value - high values are blue-violet, middle values are green, low values are yellow-red.
